      {
        "id": 2384714,
        "name": "Ian Fitzsimmons",
        "username": "Ian_Fitzsimmons",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/i/67e7ee/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2018-03-26T01:52:54.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Here\u2019s my note in 2014 on a 1999 Rapet Pougets, FWIW. I think I paid about $50 for it. My point of comparison - such as it is - would be a 2007 Jadot Pougeets, which I, personally, thought was much superior.</p>\n<p>Purchased with a 1999 Rapet Corton-Charlemagne for an anniversary dinner. Reasonably mature, though no rush, certainly, and probably some development still ahead. Not especially polished, in the style of Jadot, but I liked the slightly sandy tannins and liquorice-cherry fruit. At the price, good-value aged red Burgundy, perhaps more good 1er level than GC.</p>\n<p>I have one remaining bottle of Rollin\u2019s 2002 Ile de Vergelesses, which I guess I\u2019ll wait to drink for a few more years, judging from Jeremy\u2019s note on the les Verglesses (Rapet).</p>\n<p>After the Pougets above, I haven\u2019t been motivating to go after Rapet\u2019s wines with any ardor; but I\u2019ll reconsider.</p>",
